result.execSummary:
The defendant Dorothy Ann White was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Theft-Business Setting >$10,000, a class G felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.20(1)(b).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes:
The Defendant must set up a payment plan with the Department of Corrections for payment of the restitution, the amount per month to be $500 or what the Department deems reasonable beginning in January, 2017. 
Restitution shall be paid first to Bethany Lutheran Church until paid in full before the funds are paid to the Insurance Company.
The Defendant must provide DNA and pay the surcharge, the analysis may be expunged upon application to the Department of Justice.

The Defendant is ordered to have no contact at the Bethany Lutheran Church, with Jay Ticknor or any of its Board Members.
The Defendant is prohibited from working  in an Accounting field, or position.

03:49 PM Defendant, Dorothy Ann White, appeared without counsel.  Atty. Joseph M. Schieffer appeared on behalf of State of Wisconsin.  Probation agent, Wendy McCormick, does not appear.  Case is on for probation review hearing.  3:49 PM off the record.  3:50 PM back on the record.  Court has received a letter from [victim's representative (victim is an organization)] indicating that restitution payments have not been received regularly.  Defendant makes statement.  DA makes a statement, calls witness B.D. to provide offer or proof with regard to payments received.  DA questions witness, B.D., witness provides documentation to court through DA.  Defendant makes statement to explain her financial difficulties, offers documentation to prove medical difficulties.  Exhibit 1: financial information from Bethany Lutheran Church is marked offered and received.  Court finds that defendant has not made a good faith effort to repay the restitution ordered in this matter.  Court extends probation for 1 year and continues the $500 monthly payments.  Def requests permission to appear by phone for a 6 months review.  Court will allow her to appear by phone in 6 months, but for the review hearing in 1 year (prior to expiration of probation), defendant must appear in person.
